segments.text: Where are those?
I don't know.
Some of them I've cooked up.
Yeah, they're lovely.
Now, since you were in the Corps only for a year before you moved on to West Point, you probably didn't have a chance to exert much influence as far as becoming a leader, did you?
You didn't have a...
I don't think so, no.
In fact, I think your main objective there was...
was make good grades, or make adequate good grades, and exist, make a living.
Kept through your first year.
Do you remember what you liked and disliked about the Corps?
Oh, I liked the Corps.
What was it that you liked?
Well, I don't know, it's hard to say.
This is the first time you were in a military situation.
Yeah, well, I recognize that.
But I would say, primarily at the time, the Corps of Cadets at Texas A&M was the thing.
I mean, to be a non-member of the Corps, well, there were very few of them.
I would say there was less than 25 who were day students who were
more civilian clothes.
Did you like wearing a uniform for the first time in your life?
Well it was, it was clothing.
And I would say that that was probably had more effect than anything else is that you had
you had, I'd say money was something to wear.
Whereas, I think the first suit of clothes that I had was my graduation suit, and the rest of the time I was ready to really dress up.
you were graduating from high school.
Not that you didn't have the warm clothes and the warm, warm jacket and shoes to wear, but sure.
I don't know, I don't, I don't, at the time it was probably impressive, but the only thing that, at the time, my being in the Corps and I could

see my home was about I guess 40 miles away, 50 miles, so at that time you could thumb a ride and you could be home in an hour and a half and you could get out on the road and you'd be back to school on the weekend in an hour and a half.
Did you go home a lot on the weekends?
Well I would say probably once a month or something of this sort.
My brother
had left home the same year I did.
He stayed home for one year and had Dad out.
Then he went to Texas City and bought out, he was, well in the upbringing, he was a completely different kind of individual than I. I was the athletic type.
He was building radios, worked on
worked on watches, this type of thing.

And so he went down to Texas City and well before that, while he was still in high school, one of my uncles, one of my dad's brothers gave him a complete set of watch making tools so he could change crystals and all this type of thing.
And so he did that.
while he was still in high school and then the year he was home while he also worked on that.

And then he went down and bought this jeweler out which was just a little hole in the wall and with a room and he had bought a motorcycle and he used to come by and pick me up on the motorcycle maybe once every couple of months and I'd ride double on his motorcycle from there to

Reagan but I didn't that didn't last very long because we had gravel roads and there's always a gravel rut and if you hit that rut going too fast and you got out of it why you really got in messed up with gravel and if you went too slow why you weaved and and I think I rode that thing back and forth twice and I told them I wasn't interested in that anymore and
Because a motorcycle always ends up on top of both of us running full speed, throwing gravel all over the place.
But being in the Corps, you could get a ride anywhere.
I mean, you could go to Fort Worth.
Not that I ever went to Fort Worth, but I think I caught a ride down to Texas City one time and went down one weekend visiting him.
Easy hitchhiking in the Corps.
Oh yeah.
What way did the Corps help you?
Well, I would say that the academics helped me more than anything else.
The academics at A&M?
The academics at A&M.
I would say without the academics at A&M, I'd probably never gotten through the military academy.
Did you find the academics difficult?
Well, how did it help you?
Well, at Texas A&M in your freshman year, you had descriptive geometry.
Church's descriptive geometry.
At the Military Academy, you have exactly the same book, same course during your junior year.
Smith's College Chemistry.
It was exactly the same course that you had
same book as you had there as you have the same thing at the military academy.
Normally not the freshman year, but either your sophomore or junior year.
English being my weakest subject there, I had very good courses in English, freshman English, and then that was my weakest subject at the military academy.
stood in the 300 somewhere in English.
So I had to really work in English to keep getting found out of the military academy.
And had I not taken the English at Texas A&M, I probably wouldn't have gotten in the military academy.
And of course, my grades at Texas A&M, they accepted those on what's called a dog ticket to the military academy.
which means that you don't have to take the mental exam.
And when I reported to Fort Sam Houston to take the mental exam, well, what really happened was I went to the registrar when I got this telegram to an appointment to Westport.
I went to the registrar, and they made up a transcript of my records and sent them to the superintendent of military academy.
And then a week, ten days, or two weeks later, I got a form that the military academy required.
So I took that over to the registrar, and they wouldn't make it out.
They wouldn't make it out anymore.
Because they said they already sent one in, that's where that was at.
Well, then we, and then apparently, and then a month later, I got this letter saying they were sorry that the form at the,
Texas A&M restaurants, A&M was unacceptable, and therefore they wouldn't require the form that they sent to be filled out.
Well, I took it over and they finally sent it out.
But when I reported down at Fort Sam to take the mental exam, I had it first offered in an appointment to West Point.
John Connolly, an individual after whom John Connolly Air Force Base of Waco was named,
was a principal, and he was the nephew of Tom Connick.
So both of us were taking the mental exam.
Of course, it was very difficult because you'd been out of high school for three or four years, four years, history subjects and dates, and you're just forgotten.
And so while I was taking the mental exam,
they got a wire saying I was excused.

So I, based upon my grades at Texas A&M, I didn't have to take the written exam, and of course I passed the physical, and so Tom Cotley, John Cotley, failed the entrance exam, the mental exam, and so I got the appointment.
So your grades there for one thing, and of course- They certainly helped you, yeah.
And I would say that the subjects there are more engineering, if you know what I mean, than they are at the Military Academy.
Because as I said, the three or four subjects that I had your very first year, you have either sophomore or junior year at the Military Academy, other than English.
Did the Corps in any way, not the academics of A&M, but did the Corps, being in a military outfit for a year, did that, do you think that that had any influence on you being accepted at West Point?
No, I don't think so.
No, it's pure and simple an academic.
I think if I'd gone and had the same grades that I was accredited college by, they would have been accepted the same way.
Tom Kilday, who was attending St. Edward's University in Austin, he was accepted on a, because he attended college there and has done his grades.
And also the fact that he was a football player.
And they were interested in football players just like we are.
Yeah.
You were there for
You were at A&M for a year, and after we finish this, we're going to talk about your West Point experience.
But I've often heard many people who were former students at A&M say that it's more than an institution of higher learning, that there's something special about it.
Even though you were only there for a year, did you get any feeling like that?
Oh, I think that...
the free decor of Texas A&M students, I think it develops with time.
I think you, while you're there, and I think if I had been able to participate, you know, more into the going to football games, going to the basketball games, to participate, you're just
you become a lot more enthusiastic.
At that time Joel Hunt was a big star and if you could have seen him by you probably been a lot more impressed than you would if you just could attend.
But I think
A college where you have a corps, you do have a lot of esprit de corps that you just don't have at a pure and simple civilian college.
Going to George Washington University to get your master's degree, all you're doing is getting an education.
You're really not developing any esprit de corps whatsoever.
What did you think about the quality of education at A&M?
Well, I was very impressed at the time of the quality of education.
Well, I think Texas A&M probably is one of the best mechanical schools in the United States, although it doesn't rank with MIT.
I think it should, Caltech or some of those.
But I think it should.
as far as the courses they give and the, and how thorough.
In fact, we, Mrs. Heddington and I have four students at Texas A&M right now, and we're attending one a junior, one a sophomore, and two freshmen coming in that we are giving scholarship for.
from Falls County.
And we just set it up for Texas A&M, because I think if they go to Texas A&M, they will certainly get a good education.
Sure.
OK. Let's start making some comparisons with West Point.
But before we do that, can you tell me exactly
We've already started on how you got into West Point.
What were your feelings when you found out that you were accepted into West Point?
Well, it was very exuberant.
I mean, I would say that I was very, very happy to get there.
Really, I went to West Point because it was free.
I mean, I really didn't go there because it's West Point or the United States Military Academy.
I think my really main objective of going there was the fact that I was looking at that stage of getting four years of college and that was a way of getting it.
And you didn't think about that you had thirty years of military service that you're going to put in after you graduate from military academy.
Primarily to economic.
Let's start making comparisons then.
You said that A&M was a good academic institution.
How would you compare that with West Point?
Well, I'd say West Point is very regimented.
At the time it was very regimented.
More so than A&M?
Well, at A&M you did have a few choices.
At West Point you had no choice.
I mean, at the time that I went there,
You took, everybody took exactly the same courses.
And the only time that you deviated from taking the same course is if you were in the top 5% or something of this, some percentage.
Then instead of taking final exams, you were given

advanced courses like theory of least squares or something of this sort that you, in those fields, like if you were real good in mathematics, very obviously you could pass the final exam while you got a special course in something else.
But otherwise you took exactly the same thing
You're told exactly what to do every day, what time to go to bed, what time to get up, how to fix your bed, how to sweep your room.
It's very, very regimented.
Much less freedom than it is.
Oh, yeah.
No question about it.
What about the qualities of teacher?
Well.
I'd say both of them are adequate.
As far as architecture is concerned, you remember Professor Guise, some of the ones that you're interested in, but as far as who taught you the various courses and
I mean I don't really remember or wasn't impressed or what have you.
Whereas at the military academy you had former graduates who had gotten their master's degrees and who had gone out and had some experience and had come back to teach.
And they were, some of them were real good, some of them were
I'd say adequate, but I would think that all of them had exactly the same course to teach.
They had their lesson plans laid out for them and in every class you did exactly the same thing.
The only, see at West Point the difference, you were given a grade every week.
Right.
You were given a grade from 0 to 3.0.
And every day that you attended class you got a grade.
And on Saturday every week your grade points were posted.
And about once a month while you shifted up and down the core in classes,
based upon your grade points, so that the ones that made the highest grade all were congregated in class one.
And the next ones in class two.
I mean, in class two, in class three, in class four, in class five.
And so that your ones that made the first grade were all in the same classroom.
And I don't know, I'm really far that.
I mean, I think that where you mix everybody up, why then you have to spend too much time on the students who are kind of dumb, and not enough time on the students who were outstanding.
I always like to stay in about the second
second class.
Because the ones in the first class, they were always trying to be number one in the class, number two in the class, number three in the class.
But as you get down to take off the first 15 people, then the rest of them were kind of indifferent as to what the guy next door was making.
So at the military academy I was either in a high grade or I was in very low grade.
In English I was down in the bottom, in French I was way down in the bottom.
Well you thought that the, would you say that A&M, the quality of the teachers or professors that you had at A&M,
versus West Point, would you put those on par?
Would you say that we were better here or they were better there overall, if we could make a general statement?
I would say that that one didn't impress me, actually.
Your French professors were at the military academy and I didn't have any foreign language, I don't think.
The French professors were
Well, I mean, they were a French one.
The ones that I had, Jenner in French, was very fluent in French.
As far as I knew, as far as I was concerned, he was fluent.
The ones in math were very good.
But you were teaching exactly the same thing.
Both institutions had a fairly close curriculum then.
Yeah, I would say that I don't really remember other than architecture as to what kind of professors I had.
Did you have any military science when you were at A&M?
And I'm sure you had some at West Point.
You must have had quite a bit at West Point.
Did they teach the same type of course?
Yeah, I would say so.
Really, at the military academy, you don't have that much military science.
I mean, you have maybe a two hour course once a week, or no more than twice a week.
And you just didn't have that much military science anymore than you had at Texas A&M.
they were pretty well balanced out.
What about training, military training aspect of it?
Now you were in the Corps here, and of course at West Point everybody is, so what about the training?
Well, you're at the military academy, you're on the front row I'd say, more than you are at Texas A&M.
What do you mean by that?
Well, Path Aid News was always up there taking pictures and
and the marching at West Point and the parades and it was a kind of glamour type of thing.
Your folks back home every once in a while could go to Path 8 News at that time and to a movie and see you on the screen.
They might not be able to recognize you but because you had
1,200 people out there.
And whereas Texas A&M, you just didn't get that kind of exposure.
Was there any hazing at West Blanton, like the paddle at A&M?
They never touched you.
They never touched you.
What about mental hazing?
Oh, well, it was mostly mental hazing, but... Can you give them an example?
Well, they'd make you pull your chin in, pop your chest out, suck your gut up, and keep your eyes to the front, and some little guy, you know, about five feet forward would
come up to the tallest and look your way up and look up into your, and try to haze it and you'd almost feel like patting him on the head and say, just take it easy son, I'll get my chin in.
You had that type of hazing at the dinner table where you always had to sit on the front part of your chair and eat by the squares.
You had to
pick it up, come up, and it really wasn't bad.
I mean, in Beast Barracks up there, I think I gained about 15 pounds.
Oh, you did?
Oh, yeah.
After getting out of Texas A&M and the studying I did there, when you get on going to bed at 10 o'clock, getting up at 6,
I had good food, no financial worries.
I gained weight.
Normally, you don't.
But I thoroughly enjoyed that restaurant.
In fact, I, yeah.
Why don't they, here at A&M, they used to get away with physical contact as far as hazing
Was that against the rules and regulations at West Point or why didn't they use that?
I'm sure it was against the rules.
They couldn't touch it.
Before they could even pick anything off your string, anything off your uniform, they'd have to ask your permission to touch it.
So I would say
The fish year at Texas A&M at that time was a lot more difficult than the plebe year at West Point.
How about marching and other types of military training?
Can you compare that with A&M and West Point?
Well, your marching, see I really can't compare because I was a day student.
At West Point, while you marched,
At Reveille you had a formation.
And then you marched to Mass.
And you marched to class.
And so that all your marching was done that way.
You really, and then you had twice a week or something, military formations where you
marched on the parade ground and every Saturday you had a parade and review type of thing.
Whereas I didn't march to the mess hall at Texas A&M.
Now maybe they did at the time, I don't know being a day student.
What about the students?
You had student colleagues here, and of course, for three years you had student colleagues at West Point.
Could you compare them?
Well, as far as I was concerned, they were all about the same.
You had students at the military academy whose parents had sent them there, because that's the place to go.
I'd say a large percentage of those washed out, because they really
didn't want to be there in the first place.
But I would say probably 60 or 70% of the people were in the same boat as I. I mean, they were there to get an education.
They didn't have a lot of money.
Their parents didn't have a lot of money.
I borrowed $300.
for a deposit when I went to West Point.
And from the same bank, First National Bank, and I paid them back after I graduated four years later, plus all the interest.
But I would say that the caliber of people are, there's really no difference between the ones that went to Texas A&M and the ones that went to Military Academy.

You know, I would have thought that the ones who went to Texas A&M would have been much more rural backgrounds, probably with less, their parents having less money and where the ones from West Point would have more political contacts and maybe more urban
and maybe their parents would have had more money, or would have maybe been in more occupations like business, but you didn't find that true?

Well, see, you don't come in contact with the parents really very much, because, see, you're from Florida and Texas and California and Hawaii and the Philippines, and so you're so far away, you really don't come in contact with...
with the parents very much.
Now, the ones that lived around West Point in the northeast, the only thing you remember about them is always bringing up what we called boodle.
I mean, that's cakes and pie.
Oh, sure.
And so after somebody's parents were up there, we'd gather in their rooms and consume all of this, the sweets that they had brought up.
As far as big...
